Rode my bike up the hills and windy roads to get my ass to Brenda's. It was a Sunday, so it was a given that people would be waiting a while to be seated. The restaurant definitely had it's perks. For one, servers were very aware of their menu. That for me was a big, since most servers might be a little loose while attempting to describe the dish. Second, the vibe in the restaurant was fun, and upbeat to set Sunday brunch right. Third, is their quality of food and execution of the product was nearly spot on. Well balanced dishes, maybe slightly heavy, but, then again it was french soul food, so, BUTTER. Fourth, the price for the amount of food you get feels almost like you're at 'The Griddle' in Los Angeles, but, who am I kidding. The only negative part of the experience was the wait, an hour and half for brunch, granted the restaurant was super packed. My only question is for myself, would I wait an hour and half to eat at Brenda's again?

As I was searching for some spots to eat at while in town this weekend, I was excited to see how this place had such raving reviews and a high overall rating. We headed straight here after being picked up at the airport, and the line outside was telling my inner foodie that it'll be worth it! My party of 3 waited about an hour to be seated and we were quickly served. I ordered the fried chicken eggs Benedict with hash and well, the picture looks tastier than it is (sad face). The hash was cold and bland, the biscuit was dry and the cheese sauce on top of the poached egg tasted like nacho cheese with cayenne. My friend ordered the grillade and she wasn't too happy either... The grits were also bland and the meat wasn't anything special. What I DO recommend however, are the beignets.. We ordered the Godiva chocolate and my oh my they were delicious!! Unfortunately, 2/3 beignets we received were still doughy inside (sad face again). Service was sub-par, our server wasn't attentive and we felt rushed. I'm glad I was able to see what the hype was about, but I don't think Brenda's will be on my to-do list next time I come by to visit.

Everything else on the menu was just a-okay, nothing special. Shrimp and grits: they put a shiz-ton of cheese in this dish. Like all I could taste was cheese. Every spoonful was just cheese and honestly after the first three bites, it just gets too heavy and too much. Also after it cools, its just a harden cheesy mush. Fried chicken benedict: Again, too heavy. Not only is egg yoke heavy, but add hollandaise sauce and fried chicken, its really hard to stomach the rest. I recommend sharing. Potato hash: Mine came out mushy and overcooked. It was disheartening when you can't even enjoy the potatoes. French toast: disappointment, just pain french toast, nothing special. Was told to try this place out for brunch if you can stand the line and wait. We decided to try and go a little earlier around 9:30am and luckily seated in less than 5 minutes. Great considering there was a substantial line out the door when we left. I ordered the eggs benedict with chicken and grits and washed it down with a bloody mary.     End up having a love-hate relationship with this place. Coming here for brunch on the weekend is going to be packed, 1 hour wait at least for just a party of four.

    Let start out with the love: their Beignets are a-mazing. One order comes with three beignets and each beignet is like the size of your fist. I recommend the crawfish beignet if you are craving something savory. It's filled with spices, cheese and crawfish (can get fishy, so you have to like the seafood taste). Their apple beignets are also a delicious choice, sweet, crunchy and its like biting into a delicious apply pie.

    Honestly, I will only come here and order their beignets....only.

    Everything else on the menu was just a-okay, nothing special.

    Shrimp and grits: they put a shiz-ton of cheese in this dish. Like all I could taste was cheese. Every spoonful was just cheese and honestly after the first three bites, it just gets too heavy and too much. Also after it cools, its just a harden cheesy mush.

    Fried chicken benedict: Again, too heavy. Not only is egg yoke heavy, but add hollandaise sauce and fried chicken, its really hard to stomach the rest. I recommend sharing.

    Potato hash: Mine came out mushy and overcooked. It was disheartening when you can't even enjoy the potatoes.

    French toast: disappointment, just pain french toast, nothing special. Could have gotten this same french toast at any diner. Don't get the pecan syrup for 1.00 extra, way too sweet and not as good as plain syrup.

    Watermelon ice tea: delicious, free refills
